    id: 16,
    title: "DSSSB New Typing Test 16",
    difficulty: "Easy",
    text: `The story of human civilization is intimately intertwined with the evolution of agriculture, a revolutionary development that permanently altered the trajectory of our species and transformed the planet. For the vast majority of human history, our ancestors lived as nomadic hunter- gatherers, moving constantly in search of wild plants and tracking herds of migratory animals. This precarious existence demanded immense physical exertion and severely limited the size and complexity of human communities. The monumental paradigm shift occurred roughly twelve thousand years ago during the Neolithic Revolution, when humans in the Fertile Crescent of the Middle East made the profound discovery that they could deliberately plant seeds and cultivate their own food. This transition from foraging to farming was not an overnight event but rather a gradual process of domestication, beginning with staple crops such as wheat, barley, lentils, and peas. Concurrently, early farmers began taming and selectively breeding wild animals, including sheep, goats, pigs, and cattle, transforming them into reliable sources of meat, milk, wool, and vital physical labor. The ability to produce a consistent and predictable surplus of food allowed human populations to abandon their nomadic lifestyles and establish permanent settlements. As these early agricultural villages grew into bustling towns and eventually the first great cities, a complex division of labor emerged. Because not everyone had to be directly involved in food procurement, a portion of the population could dedicate their time to specialized trades, leading to the rapid development of pottery, metallurgy, writing systems, and monumental architecture. The management of agricultural surpluses also necessitated the creation of early governments and legal codes to regulate land ownership and resolve disputes over water rights. As ancient civilizations expanded in river valleys such as the Tigris, Euphrates, Nile, Indus, and Yellow, they developed sophisticated irrigation systems to harness seasonal floodwaters, turning arid landscapes into highly productive agricultural heartlands. For millennia, agricultural practices remained heavily reliant on manual human labor and the muscle power of draft animals. However, the Middle Ages witnessed significant technological improvements that boosted agricultural yields, most notably the heavy plow, which could turn the dense soils of Northern Europe, and the adoption of the three-field system of crop rotation, which helped preserve soil fertility by allowing one field to lie fallow and recover its nutrients each year. The age of global exploration in the fifteenth and sixteenth centuries initiated the Columbian Exchange, a massive biological transfer of plants, animals, and diseases between the Old and New Worlds. Crops native to the Americas, such as potatoes, maize, tomatoes, and beans, were introduced to Europe, Africa, and Asia, where they quickly became essential dietary staples that fueled unprecedented population growth due to their high caloric density and adaptability to diverse climates. The next major transformation arrived with the Industrial Revolution in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries, which brought widespread mechanization to the agricultural sector. The invention of the mechanical seed drill, the cotton gin, and the steam-powered threshing machine drastically reduced the intense manual labor required for planting and harvesting. The subsequent introduction of the internal combustion engine and the widespread adoption of gasoline-powered tractors in the early twentieth century further accelerated this trend, allowing a rapidly shrinking percentage of the population to produce enough food for rapidly expanding urban industrial centers. This era also saw the birth of modern agricultural chemistry, highlighted by the invention of the Haber-Bosch process, an ingenious method for synthesizing artificial nitrogen fertilizers from the air. This single scientific breakthrough artificially shattered the natural limits of soil fertility, enabling a massive global increase in crop yields. By the mid-twentieth century, the looming threat of mass starvation in developing nations sparked the Green Revolution, a global initiative spearheaded by visionary agronomists like Norman Borlaug. By developing high-yielding, disease-resistant varieties of dwarf wheat and rice, and combining them with massive inputs of synthetic fertilizers, chemical pesticides, and modern irrigation techniques, the Green Revolution successfully averted catastrophic famines in countries like India and Mexico, saving potentially hundreds of millions of lives. However, this intensive industrial approach to farming has not come without severe environmental consequences. The heavy reliance on synthetic chemicals has led to widespread water pollution, soil degradation, and a sharp decline in global biodiversity, particularly among beneficial pollinator insects.`
